Title : Billy Sprague
Text : '''Billy Sprague''' (born in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]]) is an American [[Christian pop]] singer, songwriter and producer.

Sprague was born in Tulsa, Oklahoma on July 17, 1952 to William Sprague and Oteka (Barnes) Sprague.<ref>Oteka Barnes Sprague obituary, Dowdy Funeral Home, https://www.dowdyfuneralhome.com/obituaries/Oteka-Sprague/#!/Obituary</ref>  He was raised in [[Borger, Texas]].  He attended [[Texas Christian University]], graduating in 1979, then studied English in a Master's program at the [[University of Texas]].<ref name=powell>Mark Allan Powell, ''Encyclopedia of Contemporary Christian Music''. Hendrickson Publishers, 2002, pp. 856-857.</ref> Starting in 1981 he played in [[Amy Grant]]'s backup band and also embarked on a songwriting career. His compositions would be recorded by [[Brown Bannister]], [[Gary Chapman (musician)|Gary Chapman]], [[Sandi Patty]], [[Bebe Winans|Bebe]] and [[Cece Winans]], [[Kathy Troccoli]], and [[Debby Boone]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}}

He began recording under his own name in 1984, releasing an album produced by [[Michael W. Smith]]. A second album, ''Serious Fun'', followed in 1986, featuring production by [[Wayne Kirkpatrick]] and a song co-written by [[Chris Rodriguez]]. Sprague ceased recording and performing in 1989 after his fiance was killed in a [[car crash]] while driving to one of his concerts, not returning until 1992.<ref name=powell/> During this time he continued working as a [[record producer|producer]], and produced the album ''Friends Forever Part 2'', which won a [[Dove Award]] for Best Musical Album in 1990. Switching to [[Benson Records]], Sprague released ''Torn Between Two Worlds'' in 1992 and ''The Wind and the Wave'' in 1993. In 1994, he married, and continued songwriting through the decade of the 1990s.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}}

==Discography==
*''What a Way to Go'' ([[Reunion Records]], 1984)
*''Serious Fun'' (Reunion, 1986)
*''La Vie'' (Reunion, 1988)
*''I Wish'' (Reunion, 1989)
*''Torn Between Two Worlds'' ([[Benson Records]], 1992)
*''The Wind and the Wave'' (Benson, 1993)
*''Soundtrack of My Soul'' (Mission Music, 2004)

